--- BACKCOUNTRY ROADS ---
Source: USFS / BLM Road Data — OPER_MAINT_LEVEL and JURISDICTION fields
Style File: Backcountry_Roads_Style.qml

6 rules — organized by surface type, tiered scale visibility:

  [1] CLOSED ROAD  (OPER_MAINT_LEVEL 1)
      Line — red (RGB 200,0,0)
      Width — 0.8mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:35,000
      Meaning: Road closed to public vehicle use. Do not attempt.

  [2] PAVED ROAD  (OPER_MAINT_LEVEL 5 or JURISDICTION FS + SURFACE_TYPE AC)
      Line — dark brown (RGB 80,50,20)
      Width — 0.6mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:50,000
      Meaning: Paved surface — OML 5 high-comfort or USFS paved road.
               Fully maintained. Year-round access typical.

  [3] GRAVEL / IMPROVED  (OPER_MAINT_LEVEL 3 or 4, or JURISDICTION FS + SURFACE_TYPE AGG)
      Line — tan/khaki (RGB 140,100,40)
      Width — 0.55mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:50,000
      Meaning: Gravel or improved surface. Passenger vehicles OK to high comfort.
               Includes USFS aggregate surface roads.

  [4] DIRT / NATIVE  (OPER_MAINT_LEVEL 2 or JURISDICTION FS + SURFACE_TYPE NAT)
      Line — light tan (RGB 190,150,90)
      Width — 0.5mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:30,000
      Meaning: Native dirt surface. High clearance recommended. Rocky or rutted.
               Includes USFS native/dirt surface roads.

  [5] PRIMITIVE / UNMAINTAINED  (OPER_MAINT_LEVEL 0)
      Line — grey (RGB 160,160,160), dashed
      Width — 0.4mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:30,000
      Meaning: No maintenance. May be impassable, seasonal, or abandoned.
               Approach with extreme caution.

  [6] ALL OTHERS
      Line — pale tan (RGB 200,170,120)
      Width — 0.35mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:30,000
      Meaning: Backcountry roads not matched by above rules.

Scale tier logic:
  1:50,000 and closer → Paved + Gravel/Improved appear (area planning scale)
  1:30,000 and closer → Dirt/Native + Primitive + All Others appear (field nav only)

Labels:
  Field: NAME
  Color: tan/brown (RGB 164,113,88)
  Scale: 1:1,000 – 1:25,000

