--- HYDRO LINES ---
Source: NHD + DWR combined — HYDRO_TYPE and fcode fields
Style File: CO_Hydro_Lines_Style.qml

7 rules (all visible to 1:100,000 regional scale):

  [1] PERENNIAL STREAM  (fcode 46006)
      Line — dominant blue  (solid)
      Width — 0.7mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:100,000
      Meaning: Permanently flowing water. Highest hydro priority.

  [2] INTERMITTENT STREAM  (fcode 46003 / 46007)
      Line — medium blue  (dashed)
      Width — 0.5mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:35,000 (field scale only)
      Meaning: Flows seasonally — dry in late summer. May still show
               surface water or substrate moisture for prospecting.

  [3] CANAL / DITCH  (NHD_CANAL)
      Line — blue tone  (distinct from streams)
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:100,000
      Meaning: Man-made irrigation or conveyance channel.

  [4] PIPELINE  (NHD_PIPELINE)
      Line — blue tone
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:100,000
      Meaning: Water pipeline — underground or surface conveyance.

  [5] ARTIFICIAL PATH  (NHD_ARTIFICIAL)
      Line — blue tone  (thin)
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:100,000
      Meaning: Centerline of reservoir, lake, or engineered waterway.
               Used for network connectivity — not a physical channel.

  [6] DWR DITCH  (DWR_DITCH)
      Line — blue tone  (distinct style)
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:100,000
      Meaning: Colorado Division of Water Resources ditch data.
               More detailed and locally accurate than NHD canals.

  [7] NHD HISTORICAL  (NHD_HISTORICAL)
      Line — blue-grey  (micro-dash, very faint)
      Width — 0.5mm
      Scale — 1:1,000 – 1:35,000 (field scale only)
      Meaning: Historic stream channel — may be dry, diverted, or
               buried. Relevant for placer prospecting context.

